(Nice touch with the quotes, way more subtle than all the question marks.)  You continue glossing over the issues when you keep focusing on the Priapism and discount the Phimosis.  The symptoms you keep coming back to as not a part of B in your list are not part of priapism.  I never said they were, I referred to them as Phimosis.  I also clarified that names applied to conditions were from the combination of the 2, not the one alone.  Phimosis is an inability to retract the foreskin.  It is common among infants and typically resolves itself by 5.  Circumcision is recommended after puberty if the problem is persistant.  Take a nonretracting foreskin, force it to tear frequently by an extreme and intense erection, then continue to do this a few times a day, every day until you are 13 or so and a doctor decides he will circ.  Painful, embarrassing, needless. <br>
<br>
Maybe your child is of the ideal variety where a painful medical condition striking them down in class or at play is not embarrassing, especially if it is correctable and you choose not to treat it, but my kids would be embarrassed.  The same way medical incontinence would be embarrassing or grand mal epileptic seizures.  This is not some larger social psychological hang-up on human anatomy or genitalia, this is ordinary human development.  If you fall on stage when everyone is looking it is embarrassing, if you are the last one picked for kick-ball because you may stop and double over in tears it is embarrassing, when you do things that make you not fit in, it is embarrassing.  Standing out by choice or exceptional ability is just not the same as standing out for a disability or medical condition.  I said also that it did make a difference, but not as big a one as the anti-circ extremists are trying to make out of it and I stand by that.  You will not be able to convert me from my current and considered position barring some profound evidence.  The spectrum of skepicism runs from cynic to sucker.  In this debate, the extremist anti-circ camp is the cynic, the people who circ without investigation or any thought are the suckers.  I am neither of those.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I have gone so far as to suggest a few things that it might be, what may have caused it, and what may have been a better way to prevent/treat it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I know what it is. I know what causes it. I discussed it with family and physician alike. There is no better way to treat it.  Simple circ, problem gone.  Alternatives: wait-and-see if it comes up as an issue then treat it at that stage (plus complications of surgery at that age, longer recovery time, increased likelihood of problems, pain and suffering until it can be scheduled and performed – given family history it wasn’t just a possibility, it was a probability, and a high one at that); perform continued stretching and massage exercises (doesn’t actually prevent it, only mitigates it possibly, still a high probability of ending up in surgery – in nephews case it didn’t do jack because massaging and stretching a scarred and cracked piece of damaged tissues was more like torture than therapy); skin grafting to increase foreskin size (more complicated and risky procedure than circ); medications to prevent priapism (mostly blood thinners, not allowed in children, damaging to developing bodies, risky).  Forgive my lack of approval for the armchair quarterbacking, but the arguments against circ that have been strung out before me start from the premise that I do not know what I am talking about, do not know how a penis works, discount or ignore family medical history, and argue rabidly from the basis that it is at all times wrong.  Token exceptions are being made for an adult who chooses to do it, or undefined medical cases that may exist but they will not name, (or if named are so extreme or rare as to make their argument untenable), and this is the same as never.  <br>
<br>
People seem fond of my vestigal tail analogy, one made for its comperable level of surgical complexity, but it seems to hold up fairly well as an analogy.  I would have preferred to stick with tonsils or wisdom teeth that I also listed, but since everyone wants to use the tail, we shall.  What is the significant difference between the tail and the foreskin?  It is concealed from ordinary scrutiny, so as to be a personal decision.  It occurs naturally and requires surgery to remove that can be painful (and is even more risky than circ if nerve tissues extend into it.)  So the difference seems to be that tails only occur rarely and foreskins occur in about half of all births.  Their uncommon nature renders them less worthy of protection and retention.  Oh, but a foreskin protects something that is vital and significant!  Yet no debilitating life changes arise without that protection.  No significant impacts at all occur in a properly circed case.  Some evidence is presented that it may even be beneficial, some studies support it and they are dismissed with some spurrious and suspicious reasons (uncirced guys are more likely to smoke and have multiple partners?  Please!)  We do not see statistically significant samples of circed men in counciling for pain or inability to commit to a partner or lack of sex drives.  They don’t screen you at marriage counciling for cut and uncut.  The impacts just are not as significant or abhorrent as is made out to be.<br>
<br>
My position was and continues to be, don’t circ unless you have a reason to.  My basis for that reason has a far lower threshold of acceptability than the extremist propaganda machine would feed us.  Even in the poorly decided and irresponsible case of cutting just because insurance pays for it, I do not see lasting, appreciable harm done.<br>
