<br>
If you happened to guess the correct hand he would simply say &quot;nope&quot;, but then just stand there not showing his hand, we just had to trust his word for it.<br>
<br>
You've spent a lot of time on this with me, which I appreciate, but I guess what I'm looking for would be more of a full description like:  This family was completely comfortable leaving the sons intact and were very aware not to force the foreskin back for cleaning as that would cause problems.  Their doctors and baby sitters also knew this.  When they were 2 the mom found them crying one night and they were having a priapismatic (correct word?) erection and surprisingly the foreskin had also began to tear away from the glans.  They took him tot he doctor who prescribed a topical steroid cream to see if they could help loosen up the foreskin but after several weeks of continued tearing and scarring and infections it became clear this would not work so a slit was cut in the foreskin to widen the opening.  When this also did not work they finally decided that circumcision was more humane than allowing this continue.....etc, etc, etc.<br>
<br>
Is that honestly what happened?  If so, I truly do believe it is a rare case becaues I've never heard of such a thing (have any of you who live where circumcision is uncommon heard of this happening?)  I know that you too are saying this doesn't happen to everyone, it's just that the way this story has unfolded and the way you seem unable to see circumcision in general as a bizarre practice and how the changes in the way the penis functions (not just subjectively, but real oberservable changes in how the penis works) makes me skeptical.  Anyone who has educated themselves about circumcision, as you have, should know that that is ample reason for people to be skeptical of the &quot;cousin/nephew/friend of a friend&quot; stories about &quot;having&quot; to be circumcised, though of course it would be extreme to say &quot;NEVER, EVER!&quot;<br>
